FontSize="14.25">Purpose</Run><Run>:</Run></Paragraph><Paragraph><Run> This network is the first iteration of a system for basic, human-like navigation. Consider that any three-year-old can navigate around within a home...to go to a room where she knows a desired object exists. Sallie can explore her environment and note landmarks at points where she can make a decision as to which way to turn. When she reaches an end, it notes the "color" (which can be a goal) of the destination and stores the informatization in the Knowledge Store.</Run></Paragraph><Paragraph><Run> Each landmark consists of the nearby segments. As Sallie moves, she continuously tests her surroundings for landmarks she recognizes and takes a different path in order to explore its surroundings. At each landmark Sallie adjusts her position in her internal model.</Run></Paragraph><Paragraph><Run> After exploration, firing a specific neuron initiates a search of the knowledge base for the route to that goal.</Run></Paragraph><Paragraph><Run FontWeight="Bold" FontSize="14.25">Things to try:</Run></Paragraph><Paragraph><Run> Fire the "Auto" neuron to initiate exploration and watch the entire environment be searched. Below the "Goal" neuron, colored neurons will be added as the various destinations are encountered.</Run></Paragraph><Paragraph><Run> Fire one of the neurons to the right of a colored neuron. The entity will proceed to that colored goal.</Run></Paragraph><Paragraph><Run> Open the Knowledge Store dialog box and examine the "Events" section. A Event consists of a recognizable Event (in this case, a landmark). Children of a Event consist of pairs, an action, and its related outcome. Armed with this information, the entity can know for any given Event which actions led to which outcomes. In other networks, Events contain words or phrases (or anything else) and so can form the basis for all decision-making.</Run></Paragraph><Paragraph><Run> You can modify the environment by enabling synapses and adding and deleting synapses in the Sim module. After initialization, the synapse pattern is transferred to the environment. Then you'll need to press "Set Model" to transfer the pattern to the Intern Model. Colors are randomly assigned. Mazes with multiple possible paths to a target and with open areas have not been tested.</Run></Paragraph><Paragraph><Run FontWeight="Bold" FontSize="14.25">Current state of development:</Run></Paragraph><Paragraph><Run> This is the very first iteration of this experiment in navigation and several simplifying limitations have been imposed in order to get it started out: The entity and obstacles are limited to right angles on 0.5-unit boundaries. Subsequent improvements in the way it detects obstacles landmarks should relax these requirements.</Run></Paragraph><Paragraph><Run> This has only been tried on very simple environments but there is no reason that complex environments should not work equally well.</Run></Paragraph><Paragraph><Run> Because of limitations in the vision system's ability to handle object occlusion, the maze must be stored directly into the mental model with the temporary "Set Model" button on the Simulator Module. Improvements in vision will allow this to be vision-based.</Run></Paragraph><Paragraph><Run> Touch and vision are not currently enabled. Both need upgrades to handle the visual object occlusion found of this type of environment.</Run></Paragraph><Paragraph><Run> The system presently uses a unique color for every segment in the environment as an aid to landmark recognition. This can probably be eliminated.</Run></Paragraph><Paragraph><Run FontWeight="Bold" FontSize="14.25">Notes:</Run></Paragraph></Section>
